About

A Design Practice
Built on Craft

I’m Merve Sahiner, an Interior Architect and Designer with 3+ years of experience on high-end residential projects — from villa developments to multi-unit housing. I create spaces that feel calm, warm, and quietly confident. I’m drawn to clean composition, natural light, honest materials, and details you notice over time — the kind that makes a space feel effortless, not “decorated.”

My aesthetic sits at the intersection of wabi-sabi warmth, Scandinavian clarity, and Italian modern precision. I love soft textures, refined silhouettes, and a restrained palette — balanced with one intentional moment of character. The goal is always the same: a space that flows naturally, supports daily life, and still feels elevated.

I work from concept to coordination: translating ideas into moodboards, developing spatial layouts, selecting materials and finishes, and turning everything into clear visuals and buildable decisions. I care deeply about the “in-between” parts — junctions, proportions, lighting temperature, and how surfaces meet — because that’s where the atmosphere is either made… or accidentally ruined.

I hold a Bachelor of Interior Architecture from Eastern Mediterranean University (full scholarship) and I am currently pursuing a Master of Science in Architecture at KTO Karatay University, with thesis research focused on sustainable façade materials and bio-composites. My professional path has taken me through offices in France, Cyprus, and Turkey — from intern to leading design development on 16-villa residential projects and multi-building developments.

Whether it’s a residence, a boutique interior, or a renovation, I approach each project with a simple standard: make it functional, make it beautiful, and make it feel like home — without forcing it.

If you want a space that feels minimal but not cold, modern but not trendy, and designed with clarity from start to finish — you’re in the right place.

Services

What I Do

End-to-end residential interior design, from first sketch to final install.

Concept Development

Translating vision into spatial narratives through moodboards, material palettes, and design storytelling.

Space Planning

Functional layouts that honor how people actually live — circulation, proportion, light, and daily ritual.

Material & Finish Selection

Sourcing and specifying materials with intention: natural stone, warm woods, honest textures, and finishes that age with grace.

Technical Documentation

Detailed plans, elevations, joinery drawings, lighting layouts, and finish schedules — production-ready and precise.

FF&E & Procurement

Furniture, fixtures, and equipment selection and coordination — from specifications and budgets to vendor management and install.

Site Coordination

On-site presence through construction: resolving conditions, managing revisions, and ensuring design intent survives reality.

Values

Designing with
Responsibility

I believe good design should not come at the environment's expense. My thesis research at KTO Karatay University focuses on sustainable facade materials and bio-composites — exploring how locally sourced, low-impact materials can meet high-performance architectural standards. This research informs my design practice: I prioritize lifecycle thinking, responsible material sourcing, and finishes that minimize environmental harm without compromising beauty. I am actively pursuing education in LEED and sustainable building certification to bring this commitment into every project I touch.

Thesis: Sustainable Facade Materials & Bio-composites Academic Publication: Planned 2027 Interest: LEED Certification
